I genuinely think getting a couple of claims to take into the night isn't a bad idea. Yes, you might expose someone, but you also begin to build up a picture of where we are.

This is based on the thinking that if we run someone up and they claim Seer, we're reasonably likely to only have one Good who will claim that role, and 6 Evils who might. So if someone is pressured into claiming Seer on D1, then the likelihood is that they're actually an Evil.
Which is why, generally, I'm happy voting for claimed Seers in the early game.
I'm not a fan of all-claim or d1-claim meta, so I'm less in favour of this

I'm suggesting you pressure some people, see how they react to that pressure, potentially get a claim off them and start building reads based on what others think of what happened.
That way, you don't have to wait to have intel, you're starting to build information straight away
Earlier information, even when not necessarily role claims is super strong for the Village.
Because you begin to lock in things, like two people seemingly working together.
Or someone appearing to have more knowledge than others.
These can be Good or Evil traits, potentially.
But it's actively doing something instead of passively waiting.
We know there are 6 people in this village we want to die. Why should we let them settle in and eliminate some of us and start building their narrative?

Why are we more likely to hit a Good than an Evil, when we have the option to not lynch?
If we think we're about to kill someone Good, people can vote for balance.
So, theoretically, it should take someone being egregiously Evil to make us kill them on d1

But if we automatically say that we're not going to kill, the pressure is off, and people are less likely to feel pressured about the risk of dying. Putting people under pressure is one of the best ways of getting a judgable reaction from them.
So even when balance is your preferred option, you should never state that, or those most afraid of dying will be less likely to expose themselves through that fear.
